## Secrets Manager — Store DB Credentials

Never hardcode database passwords. Use AWS Secrets Manager.

```bash
# Store RDS credentials
aws secretsmanager create-secret \
  --name prod/postgres/credentials \
  --secret-string '{
    "username": "dbadmin",
    "password": "a-real-password",
    "host": "prod-postgres.xxxxxxxx.rds.amazonaws.com",
    "port": 5432,
    "dbname": "myapp"
  }'

# Enable automatic rotation (RDS integration)
aws secretsmanager rotate-secret \
  --secret-id prod/postgres/credentials \
  --rotation-lambda-arn arn:aws:lambda:... \
  --rotation-rules AutomaticallyAfterDays=30

# Retrieve in your app (SDK)
aws secretsmanager get-secret-value \
  --secret-id prod/postgres/credentials \
  --query SecretString --output text | jq .
```

Your application should fetch credentials from Secrets Manager at startup, not read them from environment variables that were set at deploy time.

---

## Key Insight for DevOps

Always take a manual snapshot before any schema migration or major application change. Automated backups are great, but a manual snapshot named `before-feature-x-migration` is much easier to find and restore when something goes wrong at 2am.

Never put RDS in a public subnet with public access enabled. If you need to connect from your laptop, use SSM port forwarding through an EC2 instance. It is slightly less convenient but infinitely more secure.